76561198061004590,Recommended,291860,32728886,Posted: 24 June,all,HugeYetti,"The Behemoth hasn't made a bad game to date. It will NOT get stuck in early access, and will NOT dissapoint even in its current state. Highly reccomend!"
,Recommended,291860,29361210,Posted: 19 January,all,Azralynn,"See written review belowor watch it here:https://youtu.be/RsPh-mTZo8MTL;DR: SKIP TO CONCLUSION!Pit People is a strategy adventure game with turn-based combat brought to you by the developers who also made BattleBlock Theater and Castle Crashers. Pit People is a different genre of game than their previous games, but the character style and sense of humour is consistent in Pit People as well.You create a team to with up to 6 characters on it, and battle against the enemies in turn based combat until one team is defeated or your objective is accomplished. I’ve been playing mostly on normal difficulty. I always heal to full health before each encounter, and so far I haven’t found the fights too challenging. I tried a mission on the insane difficulty, and if it wasn’t for my characters leveling up (to restore them to full hp) mid-combat, I would have died for sure. You can bring more than one of the same character type at a time, but the cupcakes don’t heal other cupcakes. If all of your characters die, you lose some gold and maybe some items, but there is no perma-death, so the game is forgiving in that sense.During your turn you lock in all of your moves at once before ending the turn. If you make a mistake with the move, you can always change it before you end your turn. You are given plenty of time to lock in your moves. The combat has some random factors, like dodging, crits, and most notably which target you actually hit. You have control over your team’s movement, but you have no say as to which target you will actually attack. For example: if you place a character in a hex that’s adjacent to multiple targets, your character can attack any of the available targets, and not necessarily the target you want. There is friendly fire with AE abilities, and you can accidentally heal enemies as well.You journey out from town to explore, or complete missions by driving around the map in a nitro-boosted wagon...that poops. There are enemies everywhere, but it’s nice that you can easily avoid combat by stunning them and running past if you want to. It’s a lot better than having to flee combat, since fleeing makes all of your characters take damage, and drops your items on the ground.You can play by yourself against the AI, or in two player co-op either online or locally. There is voice and text chat In co-op, so you can coordinate easier. Both you and your ally take your turns at the same time, and there are a lot more enemies to compensate for there being a second player. There is also an arena where you can battle against other players in 2v2 battles or compete for scores on the leaderboard against AI.In almost every battle, you have the option to recruit the last remaining enemy by capturing them with a net and cage. I think it’s awesome that you can capture any enemy you come across, and that it never fails to capture. It’s also neat that you get to keep all of the equipment that they are wearing when you are recruit them. Sometimes I wish I could capture more than one enemy per battle though. There are different species that have special abilities, and other species that can be equipped with gear. There are no skill points to allocate, but the equipment let’s you customize each character.Pros:the same Behemoth style and humourlots of side quests to do, and some have their own mini stories to go with themTONS of collectible items to find - most are purely cosmetic, while others have various combat stats, and you can also trade items with other players (I played for about 10 hours, and only got 9% complete)the gameplay is fun, but can get repetitive after a while (I still got my money's worth)voice acting for the narrative (Will Stamper, from BattleBlock Theater) is amazing, and the goofy made-up language with voice acting is rather entertaining at timesmost of the sound effects are decent, and soundtrack is good, but it won’t appeal to everyone.good looking unique and colourful environments that are all designed with hexesawesome animations, and fantastic character customizationskeybindings are fully customizable, and there is full controller supportCons:the game lacks a full-sized map that shows all the areas you’ve explored - since you can only have 2 active quests at a time, it would be nice to have a large map marking points of interest you’ve seen, but not yet completednot much of the main story it available yet as expected in early access (but at least there are a lot of side quests available)(nitpick) the clouds everywhere blocking vision while driving around is annoying(nitpick) the randomness of which targets you actually hit can be a pain sometimes(nitpick) it can sometimes be hard to tell which hexes you can’t walk on(nitpick) when you are running through enemies avoiding combat the aggro sound is quite irritating (they should lower the radius that prompts the sound)Conclusion:If you’re hoping for story, there isn’t much in the way of a story campaign just yet, but there are still plenty of quests to do.  Playing against the AI as single player is fun, but it feels repetitive after a while. The co-op is enjoyable, but I wasn’t able to try the PvP since I got impatient waiting for it to pop. Overall, it’s a nicely polished turn-based strategy game that’s not too punishing, and it has an abundance of collectibles, and the sense of humour you would expect from a Behemoth title. I have no regrets with the purchase, and I look forward to more of the story being added.If you like my reviews, please feel free to join my Steam group, and follow my curationshere.You can also view this review on my websitehere."
76561198075108160,Not Recommended,291860,33303383,Posted: 6 July,all,Steve Spooky,"I was holding back on reviewing on this game, for 2 reasons. It's in early access, and I felt like I might not have known what I was talking about if I had reviewed it earlier. But at 38 hours right now, I feel like I know enough about the game to assess what's right and wrong with it (at least at the moment).To start off, let me just say that I love The Behemoth. I've never played Alien Hominid, but I've poured a lot of hours into Battleblock Theater and Castle Crashers. Both of those games I immensely enjoyed, and still play quite a bit today. So, after seeing the release of this game in the steam store about 5 months ago, I was extremely excited. Fast-forward to the first few days of the summer sale. I bought this game right away.In my first few hours of the game, I really enjoyed it. It seemed a little simplistic, but I figured that was just because I was still in the beginning. The art, music, and atmosphere were (and are) wonderful. But what occurred as I continued to play was the grave realization that perhaps the gameplay wasn't one of the strong points.Many other people have complained that battles are way too slow-paced, although that wasn't a real weak point in my eyes. My main problems were the repetitive gameplay, the lack of progression, and because of that, not much of a reason for encounters.Let's start with the repetitive gameplay. The game has somewhere around 100 quests. At the moment, there are about 3 story quests, 7 questlines, and the rest are one off quests found out in the wild. The problem with these is that there's only really 2 missions. One is to fight a battle. The other is to go to a certain point (and sometimes fight a battle when reaching said point.) On occasion a mission will have a small twist, such as having to destroy a wall, or having to protect a certain unit. Other than that though, the missions are mostly the same, with the exception of different dialouge, which is enjoyable, but doesn't help the lacking gameplay.The gameplay in a battle itself isn't bad, but gets repetitive after a while. After playing with the same team for a while, you'll see that the same strategies and moves always seem to emerge, and, most battles end up being handled in a similar way as the others. The main weak point with the repetition is that you don't get a lot out of it. This leads me to my next point, which is the fact that there is virtually no progression in the game.The lack of progression in this games stems from the fact that leveling up does almost nothing for your unit leveling up. A level 99 (max) unit might have maybe 1 or 2 more in the damage stat than a level 1 unit. If you've played the game, you'll know that this is not a lot at all. Besides that, even though there are loads of them, the items that you use on your units have mostly the same exact stats, but are just sorted into different subgroups. There are about 4 different helm groups, a few different weapon groups, and that's about it. Some of them have light changes, but this is not a lot of them. And to add insult to injury, most units can't even use items that affect their performance. For example, cupcakes (healers) are all exactly the same. The items used on them are purely cosmetic and don't affect anything gameplay-wise. Besides the miniscule stat bonus you get from tons of leveling, every cupcake's stats are the exact same thing. Humans and cyclopses are the only units to be able to use all categories as far as I know. The rest either have none or can equip one of the helmet subgroups (with the exception of the gorgon, that can equip a sword)So, the only thing you get out of capturing/encounters are cosmetic items and gold. What does gold do? It lets you buy more cosmetic items in the market, or buy supplies before you leave the town (which are going to help you get more cosmetic items.) This just lets the game boil down into two things: An insanely tedious collect-a-thon (most quests last about 15-25 minutes and only net a few items.), and decent actual gameplay that gets old quickly. I feel like more effort was put into adding more to already thousands of items, than actually worrying about gameplay.There are a few other things besides that. PvE in normal mode feels way too easy. I realize that differentiating normal and insane mode in a more free-roaming game is harder to do, but I feel like normal mode never really poses a challenge, whereas in the other Behemoth games, Normal mode posed a challenge, at least for a short time.TL;DRThe core gameplay in Pit People isn't bad. It just get's repetitive after grinding for items for a long time. If you really want to pick up this game, I recommend PvP, because I'd definitely say that it's the game's strongest point.Overall, I think my main problem with this game is that it too heavily revolves around collecting cosmetic items, instead of having some kind of satisfying progression. I don't see why people enjoy this game *so* much, but if they do, good for them. If you enjoy dumping tons of hours into repetitive gameplay where collecting doesn't do any good for you, then you'll probably enjoy this game. The thing that really hurts is that I really wanted to enjoy this game. There's definitely tons of potential for great gameplay, an awesome atmospthere, great graphics and dialogue, and abstract but enjoyable music, but that's just my two cents.5/10Major Edit 1: I'd like to make clear that this review was written during update 4. If my opinion changes in the future, I'll make sure to revisit this review. The Update 5 roadmap has just been released, and it includes some features that I'm looking forward to (Leveling, Permadeath mode, etc.) It can be found here:http://steamcommunity.com/app/291860/discussions/0/1470840994976597316/"
,Recommended,291860,29272547,Posted: 15 January,all,Retiblanc,"First thing to note is that game being early access just means the story is not complete. Gameplay is finished, and there's a lot a of quests (which vary a lot) and stuff to do, including PvP mode, and extra difficulty. However, expect that after 2 hours, you'll have finished the story in it, which doesn't mean the game ends.I loved the presentation of the game. classic Behemoth style, with a lot of humor, the same hilarious narrator from Battleblock Theater, and a lot personality behind it. Great music, with a lot of variety. For me, one of the selling points.The gameplay is also great, however, is much simpler than your average turn based grid strategy game. Your characters attack on their own if they are on range of an enemy, for example. If you're looking for ""hardcore gameplay"", you might be disappointed with it. But I think that it goes in the right direction and if fits the game, while being very accesible for people not so into the genre. This is neat because the game has local and online co-op, so you can play this with a lot of people, not just hardcore turn based gamers.Overall, i really liked the game. I would recommend it if you like the presentation, and you want to be playing it just to explore the world that the Behemoth people hace created. If you're looking for a story driven campaign already finished, wait for the full release."
