,Recommended,291860,29428482,Posted: 22 January,all,Ryan Dorkoski,"Pit Peopleis great fun!A few things definately need to be worked on and tweaked, but hey - for an Early Access game from a well-trusted developer, this is looking real good.Essentially, this plays like a modernized quirky version ofFinal Fantasy Tactics. Everything you want from a tactical turn-based party battle management game is pretty much here. Lots of collectibles, both functional and cosmetic. Definately has a good chunk of different kinds of units (the deep customization really helps here in making it feel even more extensive). The online play is off to a great start - they are doing it right.One thing I'll say right up front is that I'm thoroughly confused about people complaining about the short 'main story line' right now. First off, that's the tutorial folks - there is more coming. Secondly, there are over 100 missions WITH storyline dialogue that will certainly take you over a dozen hours to complete. Thats a conservative estimate, too.You can read about all the good stuff in, well, like every other review. What are the negative points?First off, the camera desperately needs work with local co-op. They already said they would fix this as a high priority, so fine. Secondly, while the map ishuge, it sort of, well, lacks a strong flavor. I think it feels very flat, and simply uniformly dotted with either small buildings or landscape chunks. While the map artwork is good and that is set, I'd like to see a bit of TLC go into making the terrain feel better in general. I hear keyboard and mouse controls are abismal, so be warned (I didn't try them because of this warning). Lastly, I think the music is fantastic, although it is not very artistically cohesive. One minute it is high fantasy classical-esque, then it's western cowboy music, and yet another it is techno-ish. Don't get me wrong, it is allverygood, but sometimes this difference made me wonder about how it was all chosen and put together.Another thing I'd like to mention is the difficulty. In five hours, I had never lost. Mind you, I didn't play on 'insane' difficulty, but still. I finished the 'main story', which is just a tutorial or prequal to the actual story (this version ends where it appears the real story begins). I finished 11 quests and a few other things.After a while, I got lazy and stopped really strategizing and just kept throwing units in haphazardly - and I still won.With only a few hours in, I'm going to chalk this up to early game build-up. Plus, I think online play will likely be a different story. I did play online, but only very briefly.Lastly, I felt that single player mode felt much better than local co-op. Local co-op was fun, but the screen was almost too busy, and I felt there was even less strategy. It was like 'just send the units wherever they are next to an enemy' kind of thing. It worked, which is the questionable part.Pros:+Fantastically addictive combat; everything is done really really right+Although I didn't likeBattle BlockorCastle Crashersas much as everyone else (I felt they were shallow), this game has really hit the mark with the depth it brings, respectively+Controller support is great+Don't be fooled - there is a ton of content right now; yes the 'main story' (ie. tutorial) is less than 2 hours - I assure you this will change; further, there are over 100 side quests and some 1,300 collectiblesright now(I could see 15-20 hours easy - as an estimate)+There are various parts of this game to enjoy, and it smartly lets you choose - you can turn on AI to actually do all the battling for you, which is great if you just like the larger aspects of the gameCons:-Difficulty is questionable - I can't seem to ever lose-Local co-op is just too busy to be enjoyable; it hardly felt strategic, either-While the music is great, there is no artistic cohesion; this may be fine, albeit weird-Overall, I'd like it to feel like there is more strategy involved than what I've felt so farI think this title is great, and definately worth full price."
