,Not Recommended,291860,30104070,Posted: 22 February,all,Frantic,"I bought this game based on the fact that it had an incredible 97% positive score from over 2300 reviews and Stamper voice acting. For the first hour or so I was very entertained by Stamper, but I noticed the combat felt extremely simplistic. By the last couple of hours I played it for I was half-convinced I was just not understanding the greatness that clearly must be there based on the reviews. After reading the negative reviews I think maybe I'm not crazy and the gameplay in general is very shallow.I get that some people probably really like the collectathon aspect of the game where you capture all these different creatures, but when it comes right down to it all you're really doing is moving characters to appropriate hexes and ending your turn while hoping they crit with their one attack which you don't even get to decide who it's used on in many cases.Even the gear you equip your characters with has no real effect besides a few preset options like sword with shield or sword with bigger shield. The sword might be a candy cane or a golf club and the shield might be a cake or a playing card, but that has absolutely no effect other than cosmetic customization.It seems like a lot of people are very loyal to Behemoth and I get that maybe they're also investing in the potential greatness of the game down the road, but as it stands this game is absolutely not one of the Best games on Steam in my opinion like the ratings would have you believe. I hardly ever review anything unless I think the reviews are very skewed in a way I don't agree with and this is one of those cases. I do not at all believe this game is worth $15 in its current state, but I understand why some people might buy it in good faith that it will be in the future and then some. To anyone else reading this please do more research on this game rather than relying on the review system if that $15 matters to you.Edit: Just a recommendation. I found a game called Battle Brothers that is a turn based tactics game somewhat similar to this one that I would highly recommend you save your money for over this game. The actual replay value of this other game is much higher than this one. There are far more options to customize your team beyond aesthetics and that game is highly recommended without the need for fanboys to automatically give it a positive review since it's by a studio I haven't heard of and I don't know if they even have any other games.I tried to play Pit People a few weeks ago to see if anything had improved, but the mind numbing repetitive nature of the gameplay instantly turned me off. I again highly recommend you do more research through gameplay videos rather than listen to reviews on Steam. This game can be summed up as kind of a silly chess with very little player agency. The style and vo is again very good, but the actual gameplay is garbage in my opinion."
,Not Recommended,291860,33396270,Posted: 8 July,all,Conundrum,"Take this with a grain of salt as I played this for less than an hour.This game was on the top of my wishlist for a very long time before it came out as an early-release title. I love hex strategy games and thoroughly enjoyed Castle Crashers, so I figured combining a company that made a game I liked with a genre I liked was a no-brainer.Unfortunately, I ended up putting in for a refund for two main reasons:1. The game is a console port and it shows. The mouse and keyboard controls are extremely bad. If you're willing to play with a controller this may be less of an issue for you, but strategy games play pretty badly on a controller in the first place.2. It's actually EXTREMELY casual. There's a super-hard mode available but it doesn't make the fundamental gameplay any less casual. The only command you give your characters is where to move. ALL other decisions are handled by the AI, including which character or characters within range to attack if multiples are present. What type of action is taken is handled in a relatively intelligent manner (the AI doesn't attempt melee attacks when out of range for example), but the bottom line is still that the only choice the player has is where to move.The writing and art are great as expected from Behemoth, but I just can't recommend it as a strategy game when so few options are available to the player."
