,Recommended,291860,33412483,Posted: 9 July,all,Meepturtle💌,"Pit People is a fun tactical strategy game, but it has some strange mechanics that, while relatively unique, often fall rather flat.Damage  tends to stay very low in Pit People, which can be a problem because unit health doesn't seem to follow the same standard. Taking out an enemy in a single turn is near impossible, and even healers are surprisingly tanky, which can end up making many fights into battles of attrition around a single choke point.All unit targetting is completely automatic, as a unit will target any enemy within range at random with priority given to closer targets when applicable. There are ways the player is expected to manipulate this, including making sure only a single target is within your range or flooding an enemy's range with minions and such to mess with their targetting, but it comes off as more annoying than anything else. However, there are some clever uses of this random targetting that make up for it, like one unit who can make people target other units on their team making enemy AoE units completely backfire and splash onto their own units, but those are far too chance based for my liking.There's a vaguely Disgaea-esque distiction between human and monster units, where human units have a large amount of customization for their stats and equipment while monsters are limited to a single or often no customization option/s. That being said, most of the customizations boil down to damage+dodge or defense+block for melee, and damage or number of shots for ranged characters.Probably my biggest qualm with the game though is the fact that it is nearly impossible to see numbers on ANYTHING besides damage and status infliction. How much defense does my Gorgon have compared to my Mushroom? Who knows, one bar is slightly taller than the other! How much health does my Archer have? 4 and a half hearts worth! How much is a heart worth? Who knows! How much health does that Fairy have left? Somewhere between 1/4 and 1/3, and that's all you get to know!EDIT: As it turns out, most of this can be found out if you mouse over the stats in the customization menus.Despite all my mechanic complaints, Pit People is still a very fun game, but don't go into it expecting the height of strategic gameplay or you'll be pretty disappointed."
