76561198135140705,Not Recommended,291860,35069098,Posted: 19 September,all,GeoWolf,"If you liked Behemoths other games maybe hold your horses on this one. Pit People whilst sharing an art style and humour isn't at all like those games. Unlike other Behemoth games it isnt fast paced and its humor comes from the story rather than from its visuals and its gameplay isn't exactly top notch. Its supposed to a stratagy game but bar a few differing abilities there is not much to the combat, you get to choose where your characters move and thats it. The turn based system is also painfully slow too making battles just not that fun. Every fight is just ""move here, now wait"".I also didn't think it was that funny, like i said before it puts its humor into the dialoge rather than visual gags like in other games, the world is still fantastic in many places though. The visuals are great in combat and out of it with a lot going on in the backgrounds. The story is its strongest part but as of now its just a handful of quests and a few (really good) cutscenes.This game isn't bad but it isn't ""overhelmingly positive"" in my view. If its combat got beefed up so the player would actually do stuff in it then this game would be great."
76561198084754360,Not Recommended,291860,34095615,Posted: 7 August,all,The Definition of the Cats' Pjs,"I don't really know what to write in this review, I am a huge fan of Behemoth, (I mean look at my profile) but I can't say that I enjoyed most of my time playing, in fact, my playtime as I write this review is incredibly little for me, when I get a new game I can easily spend 20 hours on it or more in a week.I was hyped for this game, and when it was released into Early Access I wanted to get it immediately, but I forgot later, and when I eventually did buy it was more because it was a Behemoth game than anything else.Probably my biggest problem with the game is it's not quite as action-packed as most Behemoth games are, this tends to be slow, and the entire gameplay is moving your characters and then your characters do whatever they want. Essentially gameplay is slow and not too engaging, it feels like an incredibly simple board game, it might NOT be incredibly simple but it certainly seems like it. Also, combat and overall gameplay is incredibly repetitive.Despite being an open-world, their doesn't seem to be much to do, in this game you can pick a quest that has little amusing cutscenes explaining the situation, then you fight. And the combat just isn't enjoyable for me, because again, it's simply selecting a character and moving them. Exploration seems fairly bland to me, the world feels almost randomly generated, being open plains with tree/mountain/buildings/water that have no seemingly real significance besides being things you need to walk around. I'd go so far as to say exploring in Castle Crashers and Battleblock Theater was more interesting. In Castle Crashers you could go through a level, find a cool new weapon, blow up walls to find hidden rooms, or even bring that one bird that finds secrets. In Battleblock Theater you could find secret rooms, and walls that looked real but you could actually walk through, leading you to treasure like gems or yarn.Treasure is also interesting in Pit People, as far as I know, there is:-New units.-New Cosmetics/Armor.-New Weapons.It seems to me from my time playing that Pit People has the most character customization, but personally with the different types of weapons and armor I think they overdid it, it's been a while, but I remember lots of different options for armor and weapons. I believe there is like 3 types of shields, 3 types of helmets, a few different types of bows and swords. Seems kind of like a lot for a game so simple. In my opinion, Battleblock Theater actually did weapons really well, weapons are so incredibly different there are lots of things you can do with each one. (Freezing ice or exploding frogs?) Unlike Pit People in my opinion, where you can trade a light shield for a slightly bigger shield. (And yes I am aware that these have minor differences, you know what I mean.)The humor, possibly the most important thing. Hmm. When I played the game, I was amused for most of the experience, but nothing sticks out as a particularly funny moment and I actually don't recall laughing at all. I won't pretend to be a humor expert, but I didn't laugh.I think it's cool that Behemoth has decided to branch out a bit from their usual (beat-em-up?) games, but personally it's not my cup of tea so far. Maybe it will be though, the game is still in Early Access, right? I don't really think I'd recommend this game unfortunately, I really do love Behemoth, but this game isn't something I'd recommend to someone (But I'd still encourage them to try it anyway) who:A: Enjoyed previous Behemoth games.B: Enjoys strategy games.As I haven't said much of anything positive in this review, I'm going to have to not recommend it. Which is causing me physical pain, I love Behemoth, and I'll try this game again sometime.If I remember more things I will update this review."
,Recommended,291860,32710846,Posted: 23 June,all,savagedab69,"The Chernobyl disaster, also referred to as the Chernobyl accident, was a catastrophic nuclear accident. It occurred on 26 April 1986 in the No.4 light water graphite moderated reactor at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant near Pripyat, in what was then part of the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic of the Soviet Union (USSR).During a late-night safety test which simulated a station blackout power-failure and in which safety systems were deliberately turned off, a combination of inherent reactor design flaws, together with the reactor operators arranging the core in a manner contrary to the checklist for the test, eventually resulted in uncontrolled reaction conditions that flashed water into steam generating a destructive steam explosion and a subsequent open-air graphite fire.[note 1] This fire produced considerable updrafts for about 9 days, that lofted plumes of fission products into the atmosphere, with the estimated radioactive inventory that was released during this very hot fire phase, approximately equal in magnitude to the airborne fission products released in the initial destructive explosion.[1] Practically all of this radioactive material would then go on to fall-out/precipitate onto much of the surface of the western USSR and Europe.The Chernobyl accident dominates the energy accidents sub-category, of most disastrous nuclear power plant accident in history, both in terms of cost and casualties. It is one of only two nuclear energy accidents classified as a level 7 event (the maximum classification) on the International Nuclear Event Scale, the other being the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster in Japan in 2011. The struggle to safeguard against scenarios which were, at many times falsely, perceived as having the potential for greater catastrophe and the later decontamination efforts of the surroundings, ultimately involved over 500,000 workers and cost an estimated 18 billion rubles. During the accident, blast effects caused 2 deaths within the facility and later 29 firemen and employees died in the days-to-months afterward from acute radiation syndrome, with the potential for long-term cancers still being investigatedThe remains of the No.4 reactor building were enclosed in a large sarcophagus (radiation shield) by December 1986, at a time when what was left of the reactor was entering the cold shut-down phase; the enclosure was built quickly as occupational safety for the crews of the other undamaged reactors at the power station, with No.3 continuing to produce electricity into 2000.The accident motivated safety upgrades on all remaining Soviet-designed reactors in the RBMK (Chernobyl No.4) family, of which eleven continued to power electric grids as of 2013."
